summary.name: Iowa Electricity Generation
summary.dataset_description: This dataset contains information about electricity generation in Iowa from different sources between 2001 and 2017.

properties.description: The year in which the electricity was generated.
The source of energy used for electricity generation.
The net amount of electricity generated in megawatt-hours (MWh).

goals.question: What is the trend in net electricity generation over the years?
goals.visualization: line chart of net_generation over year
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there has been an increase or decrease in electricity generation over the years.

goals.question: What is the distribution of net electricity generation by source?
goals.visualization: stacked bar chart of net_generation by source
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the contribution of each energy source to the total electricity generation in Iowa.

goals.question: What is the average net electricity generation by source?
goals.visualization: bar chart of average net_generation by source
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us compare the average electricity generation by each energy source and identify the most productive source.

goals.question: What is the distribution of net electricity generation by year for each source?
goals.visualization: grouped bar chart of net_generation by year for each source
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the trend in electricity generation for each energy source over the years.

goals.question: What is the correlation between net electricity generation and year?
goals.visualization: scatter plot of net_generation against year
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there is a relationship between the year and the net electricity generation in Iowa.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['year'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['year'])]
    data['year'] = data['year'].dt.year

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    for source in data['source'].unique():
        source_data = data[data['source'] == source]
        plt.plot(source_data['year'], source_data['net_generation'], label=source)

    plt.title('What is the trend in net electricity generation over the years?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Year')
    plt.ylabel('Net Generation (MWh)')
    plt.legend()
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['year'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['year'])]
    data['year'] = data['year'].dt.year

    pivot_data = data.pivot_table(index='year', columns='source', values='net_generation', aggfunc='sum')
    pivot_data.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, figsize=(10, 6))

    plt.title("What is the distribution of net electricity generation by source?", wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel("Year")
    plt.ylabel("Net Generation (MWh)")
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend(title="Energy Source")
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['year'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['year'])]
    
    avg_net_generation = data.groupby('source')['net_generation'].mean()
    ax = avg_net_generation.plot(kind='bar', color=['blue', 'green', 'orange'])
    
    plt.title('What is the average net electricity generation by source?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Energy Source')
    plt.ylabel('Average Net Generation (MWh)')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend(['Average Net Generation'])
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['year'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['year'])]
    data['year'] = data['year'].dt.year

    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    scatter = ax.scatter(data['year'], data['net_generation'], c=data['source'].cat.codes, cmap='viridis')
    plt.xlabel('Year')
    plt.ylabel('Net Electricity Generation (MWh)')
    plt.title('What is the correlation between net electricity generation and year?', wrap=True)

    legend1 = ax.legend(*scatter.legend_elements(), title="Energy Sources")
    ax.add_artist(legend1)

    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
